At the end of the trade, the Prague Stock Exchange fell to a minus
After a sharp collapse in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
CEZ shares transactions reached almost half of the day-to-day business.
From the beginning of Tuesday’s trade, the Prague Stock Exchange followed its decline on Monday when it fell by almost 6 percent.
This time, the stock drop on Wall Street is behind the drop.
Here too, the market's response to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Stock crash in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday was experienced by stock exchanges in Asia, although the indexes eventually erased some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Exchange Index in Hong Kong has written off almost four percent during trade, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to around 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stock on the Hong Kong stock market, has fallen by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai markets have been closed.
Sydney’s stock market lost more than five percent, but in the end, losses decreased to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwanese stock market, according to its index, has fallen by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of the rescue in the US is uncertain and will affect the financial markets around the world," commented Chief of Hong Kong Monetary Office Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy separately, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly return to the negotiations and approve the proposal for support of the financial system.
Otherwise, it is said that other countries will feel the effects.
American Stock Blood Bath
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected a plan of support for the financial system, for which up to $700 billion was to be spent (almost CZK 12 trillion).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index dropped by almost seven percent and recorded a drop of similar magnitude last time in 1987.
The index was falling before the vote, but once it became clear that the proposal had failed in the House, the index was in free fall.
Congress retreated: The US government can pump $700 billion into banks
US Congress leaders and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
The vote on it will be the beginning of next week.
American legislators have made a breakthrough in talks about approving a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance for the US financial system of $700 billion (approximately CZK 12 trillion).
But the game has not yet been won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final draft of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services of the Barney Frank House told Reuters.
According to sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
After that, however, we will get sober thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We've made great progress.
We have solved our differences about what the form of the market stabilisation package should look like," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi for Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers' representatives met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive form to the government fund.
It should buy unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which are pulling financial firms into heavy losses and threatening the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
It is still necessary to continue the recovery plan, but I think we are there," said Paulson.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is affecting stock markets that are falling sharply.
According to Nevada's democratic senator Harry Reid, the legislators are doing their best to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone, where Congress’ decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear for certain when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, nor whether last-minute negotiations can be stuck on a problem.
Lawmakers hope to be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will still make a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has requested.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program does not perform its function, in the sequence of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush appreciated progress in the negotiations
While the President may veto this decision, Congress may overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of a program that was to raise funds to buy out bad mortgage securities whose value had fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, remained.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciates "the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitations on golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said that the legislators agreed on responsibility for the money program, protection of taxpayers from losses, closure of concessions, timing of financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called gold parachutes for directors of the company participating in the programme and set up a committee to supervise the fund.
That should be run by the Treasury.
"We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new repayments for mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly repayment costs for debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to the chief economist Patrio Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And that is because it is not known what mechanism and at what price the troubled assets will be redeemed.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will divide their losses," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
If the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week, Mark says it's not that important.
"It is much more important that this week the Congressmen agree to support this plan and to sanctify it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on approval is most important at the moment," Mark emphasized.
Knife blade fight: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We'll advise on how to choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
From that it seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to buy a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the manner of use and the demands of the future owner.
It's hard to get home a top-notch expensive record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on LP boards and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if you are distressed by art rock, jazz or blues on your vinyl shelves, you will probably dream of at least such a gramophone.
It is the same with music on the road, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend $8,000 on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it hard to bite the headphones for 20 crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there's enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Batteries are also determined by battery endurance
Some top music players can do much more than just play music, but what most cell phones can't do.
No current device is as universal as a phone.
Besides primary functions, phone calls and texting, he can play music and video, record both, have a better one, the worse one, and maybe he can navigate.
And considering the smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of a cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than 10 12 hours, usually much less.
In this direction, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap phones, therefore, expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you make any more calls here and there, get another charger to work just to be sure - that's also true for more expensive machines.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the worse will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation per charge.
Another problem arises when you record music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but few card readers can handle miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones without reduction.
You do not need any special software for players except for exceptions (iPod).
All you have to do is fill the device with USB music from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library by name of the artist, album name, genre or user evaluation.
Some devices only display the tree structure of directories similar to the Windows Explorer and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobile phones can do more
When selecting a particular device, be particularly interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and of course also the comfort of control.
If music is primarily a set and if you listen to it every day just briefly on the tram, you just need any cell phone that plays MP3.
Which almost any cell phone can do.
You don't even have to watch too much of what music formats a cell phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and besides it, the vast majority of instruments can also handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit the respective website of the operator (or another provider) via the mobile Internet and buy a song or album.
This service could already in itself be a strong argument for the acquisition of a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this method of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones around all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening, you feel the phone in your pocket while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it depends whether you always carry headphones or at least wire handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every cell phone, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the greatest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones are normally under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns, you'll already have a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to common headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped phones with 3.5 mm holes for common headphones cost up to 15,000.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy to operate.
The simplest ones - not necessarily the cheapest ones (see our selection) - players can really control everyone.
Minimum functions, similarity of control with a previously common tape recorder or perhaps a gramophone is obvious.
There is no collision in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile Internet and then a huge data transfer account.
What devices to reach for
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchange memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card you can fit into 2,000 crowns.
Be careful, though.
Only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported for basic models.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
According to capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 CZK.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners reach for specialized cell phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
The latest is in Sony Ericsson, whose cell phones from the walkman series have the same user interface as individually sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand CZK, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), will take MP3 players away from the above mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our operators offer virtually all services such as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet there's something missing here - a virtual operator who would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, CTÚ confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation may occur - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding up so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrations over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to play on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably no longer has much chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, to which even classical operators had to respond.
Even before the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the start of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to concentrate on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a fresh target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative men vote Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a concept like that in Poland could follow us.
Vodafone's press spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations do not look very promising in the Czech Republic.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, Spokeswoman of the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to avoid any potential competitor.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera Group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them," says the group press spokesperson Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's a good time, then.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be waiting maybe until the end of the year.
For now, however, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any subject with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň, of the O2 Telefónika Press Department, told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, press spokesperson for T-Mobile, adds in rare agreement with O2: "We have not yet noticed any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it's hard to find a virtual operator.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to consider it in this short term."
Vodafone is paying attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial from a customer's point of view.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - one hand with operators
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would increase competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators want something, they can pull together is also evidenced by the movements around the creation of U:fona.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTÚ went at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
Now, however, U:fon is useful as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would impose high requirements on him and, above all, on his services."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, it is directly striking by the total lack of interest of Czech regulators.
This is not just about the CTÚ's position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for classical operators," Kristián said in response to our inquiry from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
It may not surprise the representatives of the operators to hear such a statement.
From an office to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than considered.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual operators operate normally, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In fact, the whole case is shocking to see the touching alignment of three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if it's really just a coincidence, offers itself entirely.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly just a result of chance and a hard competitive struggle.
"The Authority did not find signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has a corresponding increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said.
Interpreting a dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - it is always necessary to agree with the network operator to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are doing similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
The imposition of responsibility on the Czech Technical University is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, which the ÚOHS takes away from the whole matter.
We've met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunication Act, the CTÚ's powers to compete in telecommunications failed to be extended, although many experts had promised to improve the situation.
This must be known more than well by representatives of the ÚOHS, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one's watching.
However, the operation of pseudovirtual operators, several of which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own mobile phone prices, but they are only partially public.
They are usually multilevel marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The prices of these companies usually come only to the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company performs against the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a significant customer then gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar sales.
"If there are cases you are talking about, this could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová answered.
However, it is unlikely that a similar activity would not have taken place with responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators shall be prevented from doing so.
In fact, the activities of these companies have considerable profits, and they do not - unlike real virtual operators - endanger them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law of such speculation allows, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot have it fully with them as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that's what the CTU should be at least weird.
In addition, there is another question for the OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to similar procedures, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the OOHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they have no idea of such activities and their business conditions prohibit it.
When We Will Not Be Most Precious
As has been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decline in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were formed, classical operators tried to prevent their creation more or less.
Their arguments used were practically identical - too small, or too saturated market, problems with quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory authorities, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers, have intervened at these very times.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and they were packing more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are turning the case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we can't shake the impression that the ambiguity in competences is more than useful to them in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the rye.
If back-up information is correct and the virtual operator really appears soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be possible for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling harder than in the rest of Europe.
