Rested Gebreselassia improved his world record
Haile Gebreselassia of Ethiopia again showed why many consider him the best long-distance runner ever, when on Sunday in the Berlin marathon he broke his own world record and became the first person to run a 26.2 mile race under two hours and four minutes.
By winning the pleasantly flat track at time 2:03:59, he rolled his previous time by 27 seconds 2:04:26, which ran last year in Berlin.
Gebreselassia, who is 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is truly incredibly wide - he has broken the world record or is at least a world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassia missed the Beijing Olympic marathon because he was afraid - perhaps too scared in retrospect - that air pollution upsets his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at start, 55 degrees at finish - won on Sunday Gebreselassia with a flashy average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since track runners like Gebreselassia and Paul Tergat from Kenya focused on longer lines, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the last decade, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won Berlin at 2:06:05 in 1998.
After the victory on Sunday, Gebreselassia told journalists that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
Apparently, the break was more of a wake-up call than a delay.
"I am so happy," said Gebreselassia to reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started over a week ago, and I was a little in doubt today, but everything was fine."
He was also criticized - mainly in Kenya, the East African rival Ethiopia - because he was said to have over-planned his races, generally avoided world marathon peaks, relied on conductors, as if it were a race on a track, and built world records above the sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly reduce Gebreselassie's enormous running qualities.
Maintained at a pace of four Kenyans reached Gebreselassia half in time 1:02:04.
After the conductors fell off, two elite Kenyan runners James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi were constantly chasing Gebreselassie.
A little earlier than three miles before the goal Gebreselassia took last and escaped Kwambai, who then ran second in time 2:05:36 and thus improved his personal maximum by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in time 2:07:48.
In the women's race, the seventh fastest time of history 2:19:19 Irina Mikitinenko, a native from Kazakhstan, who is now a German citizen.
Record time 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
Thirty-six-year-old Mikitinenko surprisingly won last spring at the London Marathon at 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games because of something that was described as a back injury, but she recovered and won in Berlin and in the third marathon, which she had ever run, improved her personal maximum by almost five minutes.
She ran the race cleverly and thoughtfully: she let four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners escape into a big lead and then dragged them about 18 1⁄2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in time 2:25:01.
Proudness and obstacles to the lives of black people in a separate city
Hidden among the vast amusement parks of the Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and intensity of African-American life come to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guava, two schools, and no prison."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville festival Zora! to pay homage to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, even though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that country blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many residents here remain wary of foreign views.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the black rise and a community of almost 2400 people, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is the center of literature, but also oaks shielded by an example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - which came from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way to say Hurston here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through hearty books full of dialects like "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide changed the city a bit into Route 17, which leads through the often ephemeral center of Florida, to the stage of black history and human drama.
With the shock of a big drum in her life and literature, Hurston introduced the reader to the store of the first Eatonville mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into an hour-long hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville connected with self-government, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Obviously, this wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy - seven - year - old Augustus Franklin recalls that, most of the time, when she rushed into the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevy, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of dignified clothing.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many scoffed.
"People always liked to see Zoru," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
It seemed like Eatonville had forgotten about her and the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920 ’ s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived.
There were no major funeral ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance in the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography "Wapped in Rainbows" published in 2003.
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the five-way highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is a local two-way main road.
Orlando's climbing has already pushed interstate highway 4 through the west edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, has ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950 ’ s, the struggle to stir up races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at people who sat on the side," Franklin said.
"In fact, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel of 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration and declared his decision against the Education Chamber against Brown to be "offensive to my race rather than celebrating."
The inhabitants now claim that desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the youth here.
"Black children were used to hugs - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You are not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there is a cultural barrier," said Ms.Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped create room for many other Zory Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to the unmarked tomb of Hurston and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, he came to the shelves at the bookstores and praised the resume of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, who re-entered it in the American Canon.
The highway project arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the ramp lights again.
The former Hurston neighbors now saw her as a savior.
In 1988, the community began planning the Hurston Festival to show what could happen to its highway.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway design.
"The five currents of the highway raised up, you'd say it detonated directly, real civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd said it easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Winning the highway project helped change the city's image.
Extra-urbans like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started going to the local church in 1993, began to appear in more numbers, and the inhabitants began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 at the re-academized and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes seem like a dark alley in the summer rain as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880 ’ s.
(Today is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come looking for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated cautiously.
Permission for most interviews is necessary in advance and certain things - like murals in the oldest eatonville church, painted by white people and depicting black people in fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a courageous, confident teacher who likes deep red, are still worried that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival got bigger, so did home pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, there is a sincere love for the community when she plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, who she says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11 - year - old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass by, think, 'Well, this town is nothing against the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice town."
Here in New York, we're all fluent in finance.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan had stayed away from newsstands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they would not have realized that they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in a glazed bee hive of offices above their heads, every day bankers and hedge fund managers monopolizing New York have the worst "bad day in office" since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers are still raving with metal carts on the sidewalks and carrying muffin pans to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between towers and carry, like human mules, 50 ironed shirts hanging from the scales on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it is still not possible to get a yellow cab on weekday between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m.
It didn't look like a crisis at all until, with all the pessimism talk, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this assignment to cover with a late afternoon siesta at my local branch, JP Morgan Chase, there were about 20 people waiting in line.
Not in front of cash windows to collect or store cash, but in front of the counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's mixed goods store and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason I did.
However, compared to me, they have already raised their savings from smaller banks in places they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They raised money from so-called thrifts (a little bit like building savings banks), money associations, and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and who claim to care for their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks went silently bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion worth of assets, went into bankruptcy, and when the New Yorkers were coming home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion worth of assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
Employees of offices and shops standing in front of me, afraid of another collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the saving on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned fluent finance over the last week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, the failed bank, and to her skinny chief executive, Dick Fuld, with such a familiarity, as if gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, a uniformed 50-year-old landlord of my tenement, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation-- Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she said to me, "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I moved it, I'm not taking any chances."
Muslim graves desecrated after the Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, from the Austrian Right Party of the Free and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian Right Party Vlaams Belang participates in the demonstration which presented in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008 the organization "City against Islamization".
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that show mosques crossed out by the red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating the Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend in which extreme right-wing parties made huge profits in general elections.
Over 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were sometimes severely damaged between Friday evening and this morning and the police believe it was an organized event.
The culprits sprayed Jewish symbols on some graves, such as the star of David, but the detectives believe that this might have been an attempt to mask the motives of extremists led by hatred toward Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether this incident was in any way linked to the elections.
A spokesman for the Islamic community here said that they are "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration coming as the Muslim Lent Month of Ramadan approaches the end.
Meanwhile, Austria enters the round of searching for its own soul after the right swings in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
Both ultra-right parties, which won more than 30 percent of the votes, the Free Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, led a vehemently anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the Free Party, who won over 18 percent of the votes, protested against scarves and burkas in the campaign, and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At the last meeting with voters in Vienna he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets and argue that these are political symbols of the ongoing Islamisation of Austria and Europe.
The surveys and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right in the position of the country's strongest political bloc, indicate that this change was caused primarily by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
