"To capture the true character, I take pictures of the master outside the scene." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no calls, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great flamenco masters, free from focusing on interpretation - I will only achieve the relaxed expression of a man or woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other hand, human.
Inseparable, aside from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then you can see the intimate gesture, the depth of the glimpsed glance or the passionate gesture of hands that are carefree because they are not going to appear on the stage.
German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatrics with singers, dancers and guitarists with that less known face of masters.
With this intention, the photographer builds a unique iconography of flamenco from various backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place within the framework of the Flamenco Moon (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), "reflects the ever-growing international meaning of flamenca", says the author and explains that "Flamenco-people" "may be any kind of person, but when you look at photographs, you will find that they are not typical pictures of artists on the scene.
These people portraited "on the street" are artists capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He wears his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portrait flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the image and lends it the present spirit, an idea reflected by the flamenco himself: "Music with very traditional roots, which, however, continues to surprise and evolve."
What tears down the audience is not the action of dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most important, the spirit that appears in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that was and is the constant of work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
This selection of almost 70 photographers is made by famous flamenco characters such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Moreente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of flamenco anthology and will soon see a book release, which will contain exhibited portraits.
The passion for portraitry led Bauer to the idea two years ago to repeat the idea of a "Portréte sports veteran" ("SportART project").
Although their concept from "Flamenco-people" is different, the photographer admits that "photographing people, getting to know them and having the opportunity for a moment, whether longer or short, to enter their lives - that is my passion.
I think in the photograph, the portrait is the most difficult genre.
One encounters or encounters people, personalities that sometimes do not even know, or only give them a few minutes to shoot.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is exhibited at the Gallery El Fotómata in the street de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hercules, and can be visited until 16 October.
