Sevilla flamenco dancer pays tribute to another Sevilla dancer.
Carmen Tortola Valencia, from the father of the Catalan (Florenç Tortola Ferrer) and the mother of the Andalusan (Georgina Valenciana Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and when she was three years old, she and her family moved to London.
She danced modern dances and focused on oriental dances.
She lived a life of passion, pioneering a woman's emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf, or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and she fought for the abolition of the corset, which made it impossible for women to move freely.
This woman's life, influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe, has bewitched Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this character - it seemed incredible to me."
According to the dancer, "it's not about telling her life, it's about grasping her soul.
The names of her dance performances reminded me of flamenco rhythms.
So the "dance of the butterfly" evoked guajira or "dance of the snake" some thong.
Her dance was sensual and told me that my dance of this aesthetic also corresponds," she says.
The performance counts with the involvement of two exceptional personalities: Miguel will lead, who will sing Isabele in one performance as well as in the "Open Doors" (La puerto abierta), and with the dance teacher Matilde Coralová, who made an exception and agreed to cooperate with her former pupil.
"Matilde represents the older Tortola, a mature figure.
I am happy that she has accepted an offer to participate in my project, and it is a great honor for me."
The performance also includes the music and guitars of Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; the drums of El Pájara, the viola of Rafa El Viola and the co-operation of the actor Juanfry Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal guide of this kind of artist, who are primadonians with all things, and who are always in love with them."
The work also takes into account the life of this woman, who took place at such a long distance, such as India, the United States, or Russia, as well as throughout Europe, because she usually resided in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think she was of those women who have a huge influence at some point, but today nobody knows her and even less appreciates her work," says Bayón.
