Drivers caught repeatedly with alcohol in their blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Interior Ministry requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol have to install a system in his vehicle that prevents him from starting his car drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal was already known in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Prosecutor's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
Its aim is to get the driver back behind the wheel, which is why drivers will also have to take a course in transport reeducation.
In addition to the National Transport Safety Authority, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for the Safety of Cars (FITSA) will participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 % of car drivers charged with more than once for drunk driving will again get behind the wheel in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this because it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if the alcohol concentration is higher than the permitted concentration.
Its price exceeds EUR 1,000 and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study carried out in this sense in the US in 2007 showed that infringements had decreased by 65% for vehicles equipped with this equipment during the first year since the introduction.
In Spain, 115 people are expected to be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, as legislation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary regulation of criminal provisions, however, requires the amendment of the law.
The equipment is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been installed in some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Members will vote on the proposal by the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) in which it is recommended to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
