Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us what happened the day before, but the kids who talk while they sleep.
The first time this happens, it may scare you, but it's actually meaningless.
It's a harmless sleep disorder called the somnoly.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure not one of you has been told that he spoke in his sleep last night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadicly (e.g. once in a lifetime in high fevers) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There's only one reason why she's coming.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fury, enuresis nocturna (night urination) or sleepwalking, but it may not be.
As mentioned earlier, it can often accompany very high fevers, stressful or turbulent situations.
In any case, this is a minor phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or quite the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases of great strength, it would be advisable to observe and consult an expert to see if he has a problem that causes him great anxiety and manifests himself in this way.
We said it was a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to upset the baby too much before she goes to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who can work to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more calmly.
When the somnilovia appears, try to remain calm.
Recall that she is harmless to the child and that she will remember nothing of what happened the next day.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're gonna interrupt his sleep.
Even when he talks, he sleeps, and he rests.
Remember, if several times in a row you feel that she is in great pain, it would be advisable to seek advice or to find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If it is understood what he says (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and draw information from him.
It won't do any good, because when she's asleep, she's not conscious enough to organize her thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he dreams about, and therefore why he says it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you draw.
Never tell a kid you can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Just don't worry, it's nothing wrong, it's just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
