Interview - Blood that is sure again
Yesterday, Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the public’s confidence, which was seriously shaken after the blood - contaminated scandal in the 1980’s and 1990’s.
As is generally known, the national blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Canadian government launched a public investigation chaired by Judge Horace Kráter to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Kráter tarried to report, some provinces set in motion a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was played by the Gelinea Committee.
After Gélineau and the Kráter report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was to run Quebec, and the Canadian blood company for supplying all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec began his activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," recalls Dr.
"The situation was daunting.
With a consistent effort to increase the safety of blood products and permanent work in this area over the coming years, we have regained public confidence," Hema-Québek said, proudly adding that almost 94% of the Québek population trusted in early 2008.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998 Hema-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"Then we witnessed many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Kráter and Gélineau's report, according to which, if we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures must be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, the disease was safely proven to be transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to follow the principle of prudence."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for HIV virus detection appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood rather than the presence of antibodies on which tests were based before.
The NAT tests enabled the deaf period to be shortened between the moment of the patient’s infection and the moment when our techniques in the blood may reveal the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have allowed the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions to be significantly reduced.
Today, one in 12 million people are exposed to the risk of receiving HIV - contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission via blood products occurs.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for recovery," says Hema-Québek, head of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease element can appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like West Nile, is transmitted into the blood by insect stings.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," Dr Décary continues, stressing that besides safe supplies, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment for cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation."
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, which means six times a year.
On average, 14% of those offering blood are not accepted, for example, because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a land where mud fevers are rampant, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
But it is difficult to persuade people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to give blood," Francine Décary writes.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Québek, which also manages the only public bank of cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, has blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the umbilical cord into the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all the hospitals in Quebec.
