It was Vic Toews, the ex-minister of "justice" in Harper's cabinet, who took the liberty of saying about Louis Arboure in the summer of last year that he was a disgrace to Canada.
In this way, to disgrace a woman who has waged an unfailing fight for justice and who deserves all our admiration, this speaks to a great deal about the Prime Minister's surroundings and Stephen Harper himself.
We have before us a government that, as the only one of all the Western countries involved, has not brought back to its homeland a national locked up in Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that has no regard for the fact that Omar Khadr was a young adolescent at a time when the actions he was accused of were to take place.
The only government that, despite Canada's signing the Geneva Convention, denies its word and lets a child soldier rot in in inhumane conditions.
