Opinions - Orwellian discourses by Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwell's logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has begun to prosecute three authors and a poor little publishing house for libel in order to provoke a "transparent public debate" and demand six million.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for libel, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver's radical resolution is completely passing.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate, to ruin anyone who dares defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and to fight a very uneven battle with an army of lawyers supported by almost bottomless pockets of mining company.
After all, the tactics in these unbalanced battles often consist in bankrupting the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will clog the counterparty’s mouth and, moreover, dismay anyone who dares to pursue this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of the whole thing to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, Canada normally has a debate in exchange for ideas rather than a baton.
Thus, mining companies were not enough to open up their books, their documentation, and to bring real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion, and he rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a 'public debate' and, at the same time, despise the opinion of the same public?
In the vice president's world, that word seems to refer to only fat-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept of that concept.
In a democracy, even libels have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because he rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is prepared to hear and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in the context of what many see as prosecution, in which the defendant is to be blocked (in the context of his prosecution of the "public debate", Barrick has just presented an official invitation to Noir Canada authors to officially announce that they should stop using this term...).
Apart from the surreal Garver speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of exploration and the search for the truth that is essential for every democratic society.
Overall, he denies the right to citation of credible sources and to the debate about facts and interpretations that are itself the basis of intellectual activity.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that do not like the rich companies of this world without being subjected to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could be created if it followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada’s authors.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that despite what he claims, he has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures that would limit such a type of wrongful prosecution.
