A new version of the plan, using $700 billion to slow the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months, must still be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the payment of stored public money, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payments, and also the right to monitor the level of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
US Finance Minister Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and we have reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disruption of American daily life will be huge," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last hours, negotiations have gone to maximum speeds for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors’ state of mind.
The time limit was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US President were invited to negotiate later, and both expressed themselves rather in favour of an agreement, but without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added to the agreement on certain measures, in particular the aim of allowing owners to remain in residence, and on the wage of the head of the state of employment of the rescued companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures for some people's irresponsibility, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the television waves.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station to vote in favour of the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I've read show that it's something we're all going to have to spend, and it's going to be possible to move on.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The objective of the 700 billion plan is to buy out dubious receivables and risk and non-saleable assets from US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by the bursting bubble in the real estate market, which first led to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the decomposition of banks and financial institutions.
The failure of last week's first draft agreement was caused by Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats agreed that the government would only guarantee some of the "toxic" assets of companies having difficulties, but not buy them, there is a belief that the impasse is averted.
In an effort to bring conflicting views closer together in Congress, a measure was added that the government would be able to introduce new charges to help her regain her deposit if, as a result of the programme, she had to take on losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add an additional 100 billion if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in saved companies, which, in the event of profits, will pay him dividends and which it will be able to resell when this is over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of property associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The directors of the plan would like to put him to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project in both Republican and democratic camps.
"It is quite obvious that Washington can't hear you," declared Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's financial committee, to the electorate.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, making money on taxpayers is not the answer."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed "the Skeptic Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but it comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred respected professors of economics, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to examine carefully which route to take," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for EUR 11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French Bank of BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from buying its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of risk loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, among the 20 largest European banks and among the ten largest insurance companies.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is what savers and households today can appreciate."
On the other side of the Channel La Manche so far, the British government seems to have launched the nationalization of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than USD 41 billion (75,5 billion) constituted loans to buy real estate.
According to her announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will purchase branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government must nationalize from the start of the financial crisis.
