What was produced in the Zuschlag & spol. invoice factory?
Soon, October 8th, the trial against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
Among other crimes, including forgery of documents, the politician and his associates are accused of fraud committed in the long term and systematically by a criminal organisation, which has caused extremely significant damage.
According to the prosecution, they used the money obtained in public competitions for their own purposes and often documented the fulfilment of their tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and self-government - totalling approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the Fiatal Ballodal treasury, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The way he also informed the investigating authority was that the money received in the tender was collected on the basis of invoices which did not give rise to actual consideration and the undertakings accepted were never fulfilled by the associations.
According to the prosecution, a lot of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Yozsefros market, and round stamps were produced in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of which companies are to produce invoices have been decided, among other things, on a sightseeing tour along the northern bank of Balaton, on which István Ladose János Zuschlag sent.
According to his testimony, the first name was to look for boarding houses and restaurants.
In them he asked for bills for his consumption, according to whose model invoices were then produced in the framework of public competitions published by, inter alia, the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and, respectively, the Self-government of the Capital.
The invoices were mostly exhibited by István Lados with his associate András ?ri, who according to our information wrote the most often the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip" Lados looked up a beer hall.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, this catering establishment provided catering for a 90-member group from Biztos Pont.
However, according to the company manager, so many people would not suddenly fit into this facility.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer 2002 to Jobb Jövőért, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was swarming with formal and content errors.
The pension in Badacsonytomaji had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet an invoice included 130 guests.
However, the fillers of the forms with a rich imagination overtook it even when they listed on the documents of the company involved in the hospitality - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounts according to the information provided to the prosecutor's office documents in the name Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even figure.
The head of Győző Farkas for hvg.hu said that when he was summoned to the D.A. and showed him invoices, he immediately knew it was false documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were stamped in the wrong place."
As he added, in addition to the formalities, it was not agreed that according to the invoice they had accommodated a hundred people, because they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also included catering, with their restaurant no longer working for a long time.
Zealous invoice manufacturers did not even convince themselves that the sought-after Budapest travel agency only organises foreign trips, and on the invoice with cash payment, which also did not match the company's billing practice, foolishly referred to it as a travel brokerage service in Hungary.
Moreover, as was apparent during the investigation, they also indicated VAT in the document, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
The four documents issued by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. did not agree either with the amount of VAT. The company’s activities are not covered by the 25 % but by 15 % VAT, and in addition the hotel staff issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "publishers" corrupted the invoice, for example, by stating with one company how it became apparent thanks to the prosecutor's investigation, as a road transport activity, which was not originally carried out on investment advice.
The fact that invoices issued by the Együtt Foundation and Harmadik Évezredért and the association XXI. Szazadi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false, also because of formal deviations - not corresponding to the format of the invoice and the incorrect stamp.
As with Ravenna k.s. or the Sport Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied that they would issue invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not even notice that HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time of the 2001 meeting of the Fiatal Városért group, which is why according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
The invoices were exhibited consciously
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Eséla Budapestért Foundation has issued accounts for around four million forints for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Ballodal - Ifju Szocialisták organization.
