The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people do not want to lag behind in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research was using an experimental auction to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in the stage auction, examining the active areas of the brain of experimental subjects using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, the important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively when losing.
This brain area plays, among many other functions, a role in the "self-remuneration" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to researchers, it is therefore possible to explain the unscrewing of the price by avoiding the sharp reaction of the stretch marks.
To support their theory, members of the economists’ research team conducted a financial cross-cutting survey.
Three groups cite against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made bets.
In addition, members of another group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive $15 more in reward.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost this money as well.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was all about stressing one’s win and the other’s loss.
However, members of the group playing "against defeat" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winner" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, these have explained phenomena observable in auctions for the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
It was neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we now came to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are treated, often because the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, typical of inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the origins of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways, depending on the underlying disease: hepatitis A and E to the digestive tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travelers should in any case be protected by vaccination against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against a type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after taking an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
After that, jaundice, light stools, and dark urine are formed on the skin and the eyes. The treatment may last for two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people around the world die of a more serious type of disease, liver cancer, and hepatitis B liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is that estimates are that only one in ten infected patients are treated medically.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to hepatic cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know about their disease, causing the disease to destroy liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms occur in many cases up to 20-30 years.
It is therefore very important to prevent early, to carry out regular writing.
In three groups, this disease occurs a lot more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already show routine laboratory testing, a person should contact his or her physician if he or she notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent infection and to prevent cancer.
September 30th is the world day of hepatitis, which was organised by organizations representing the sick for the first time worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, to the causes of it and to the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
According to recent research, faith in God works as an analgesic that might have facilitated the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, researching how man’s faith in the god of pain affects, reported the British daily Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre survey, they subjected 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists to electric shocks, while all watched the painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
The technique of examining the human brain has also shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
Research is the first of a series of researches involving scientists, philosophers, and theologians from various parts of the university alongside academics.
The exact test was carried out by attaching a spark instrument to the left hand of the test subject, which produced electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe the two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary, dating back to the 17th century, and the Lady with the Edge of Leonardo da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of Our Lady would create a certain state of piety for believers, while Da Vinci’s image was chosen because they did not differ much from the first one and seemed to make a calming impression.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time received in four consecutive parts 20 electroshocks, while separately watching the picture with religious or general topics.
Catholics said that when they looked at Our Lady, they felt "safe," as if they had been "taken care of" and "calm down, filled them with peace".
They felt 12 percent less pain in watching a religious picture than when they had Leonard’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved by means of any powerful image even in atheists, just to find the right photograph.
"We would have to find an image that they will perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," said the psychologist.
The English bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases it will also change our personality," Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the regulation of the pain of believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of similar caliber.
Would the view of the quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
