Smart Car Imitates Bumblebee Flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
With bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of a surprising project presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC was inspired by engineers from Nissan Bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of collision prevention systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan designed a biomimetic robotic control system such as BR23C, a robotized minicar equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is in fact very similar to our safety cover," Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technological PR and research and development.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions of view.
To copy the function of the folded eye, engineers reached for the idea of the laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of BR23C in the 180 degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which will instantly be transformed into an operation aimed at preventing collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts imitating the movements of the bees and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver is taking place in an entirely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, a robotic car could not respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Lab and robotic car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective package, which is currently considered inevitable within the collision.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not last longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotation, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reactions are important, not processing ability, the less data storage.
This mechanism must only process and respond to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store them and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore they constantly use only memory of the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with a giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate avoidance technology that, according to Nissan, could reach serial-produced vehicles within ten years.
Another option of application may be the connection of the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles.
