After further negotiations, which ended on Saturday after midnight of American Eastern time, Congress officials reached an agreement in a few days of debate over a $700 billion bailout, said Reuters.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the democratic president of the House of Representatives, according to which only the drafting of the agreement remains.
Both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain also supported the compromise on the package.
Minister of Finance Henry Paulson said about the outcome of the compromise: "The programme will work and it will be effective, but further action needs to be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 o'clock in the evening of Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2 o'clock in the morning of Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise on the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the draft legal standard, hearing in the name of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act, which is to be established by the programme, then it will be the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then the news of the agreement was also welcomed at the White House.
"We are satisfied with the progress made at night and appreciate both parties' efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said spokesperson Tony Fratto.
After all, the program differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which was intended to make the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities spend an entire $700 billion at once.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of $700 billion in the first round, so that $250 billion will be used immediately after Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, and the Treasury will buy mortgage-backed securities, which are rated as poor, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the president's decision.
The programme will be controlled by a special corps, the chairman of which will also be a member of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on Congress' next decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic within the meaning of the Act: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poisoned" loans.
The purchase can take place directly within the auctions, and the competent representatives of the Ministry have informed them.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance grants them a guarantee for the means constituting cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of damage expected.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to meet the urgent demands of the US financial system, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to introduce the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting to help the state can count on the government to cut their severance pay - which is simply called a "gold parachute" in overseas slang.
They will be limited only in certain cases, and these restrictions will depend on the mode of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax premium will be imposed on gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the event of a direct buy-back of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively take action to ensure that money for management is not exaggerated.
It should be added that the already existing gold falling treaties will not change, the restriction concerns only new ones, which is to be another incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first case in American history to have legal restrictions on the remuneration of CEOs in force," commented the Chairman of the Committee on Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
Moreover, the state in the banks participating in the programme will have the right to acquire a stake, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, since once the economy and the saved bank are on their feet, they can also make money from this transaction.
