Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 due to the previous month, then by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent year on year.
Production prices in industry were 0.7 percent higher as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, rising by 3.2 percent yoy.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by at least 0.1 percent due to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the luggage and saddlery products sector by 4.6 percent, respectively, and footwear production by 2.5 percent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical and product production sector (1.6 percent).
Prices were reduced in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we have measured the price increase in the range 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water distribution sector, which has a large weight in domestic sales to the industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly by the continued effect of the officially established increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in each industry, prices increased most in the oil processing industry (32.4 percent).
In the co-production sector, 13,2 % could be observed, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products with a decisive weight, then 11 % increase in prices.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile industries (2.5 percent) and in the electrical machinery and apparatus production (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2% during the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water industries exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
From the point of view of the sector's focus, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the material asset production sector was shown on domestic sales in August.
In the consumer goods sector, prices increased by 0.3 percent; in the energy processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change in relation to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 in relation to the same month of the previous year was observed in energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, we have measured an increase in prices of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, we have measured a fall in prices of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened 1.7 percent in relation to the euro in one month, then 7.1 percent in relation to the dollar, increased 7.5 percent in relation to the euro in comparison to the euro in August 2007 and 15.9 percent in relation to the dollar.
